ozee:
I came up with a solution to this by adding a clock to the slider.
javascript
Superslides.prototype = {
  clock: 0,
Setting a global variable for the clock. And then refactoring the start function:
``` javascript
start: function() {
  var that = this;
if (that.options.hashchange) {
    $(window).trigger('hashchange');
  } else if (that.options.play) {
    window.onload = function() {
      that.animate();
    }
if (this.play_id) {
  this.stop();
  that.clock = 0;
}

this.play_id = setInterval(function() {
  that.clock += 1;

  if(that.clock === (that.options.play / 1000)) {
    that.animate();
    that.clock = 0;
  }
}, 1000);

} else {
    this.animate();
  }
this.$el.trigger('started.slides');
},
```
To resume the clock I built in a resume function as well:
``` javascript
resume: function() {
  if (!this.play_id) this.start();
this.$el.trigger('resumed.slides');
},
```
To use this, you would use it like any other API call,
javascript
$('#slider').superslides('resume');
